body:
Hello,

With only the default options enables, the PlantUML output shows inheritance (e.g. `AddCar` inherits from `Transaction`, `Car` inherits from `Vehicle`) and so on. Would there be any interest in adding more information and relationships to these diagrams? 

I've hacked on my own version of the extension to add additional information for relationships and concepts inside transactions, assets, etc. My goal has been to get a better image of the relationships of the various entities in use within the blockchain.

As a tiny example, the following CTO file:
```
namespace org.example

transaction AddCar {
  o String model
  o String year
}

transaction RemoveCar {
  --> Car car
}

asset Vehicle identified by registration {
  o String registration
}

asset Car extends Vehicle {
  o String model
  o String year
}
```
might be visualized to include the relationship from `RemoveCar --> Car` as
![screen shot 2018-10-30 at 6 51 10 pm](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/484114/47709997-f9cbcc00-dc74-11e8-85ab-ec9a38d0bb18.png)

Is this something you would be interested in merging into the extension? I realize that since the way things are visualized might often be up to individual preference, it might be difficult to find something that can fit all users, but I'd be glad to discuss this further if there is interest.

This task is to perform the first part of the unit test delivery for the **server** side of the VSCode extension, required within #61 

The deliverable here is the complete outline and delivery of test stubs that will cover the client side. 
- all tests to be described in the mocha framework:

```
describe('such testing of VSCode extension ... ', () => {
    describe('#myFunction', () => {
        it('should do blah', () => {
        });
        it('should not do blah', () => {
        });
    });
});
```
- no test code to be written, we are only interested in considering the required unit tests to be applied

The aim here is to understand how the client side code is operating and how best to test it in a unit fashion. Once the tests have been scoped, it will be possible to move on to test code delivery and setting the code coverage requirement in istanbul to 100%

